         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
            <p>Of the Mamertines</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>
               A group of Oscan-speaking Campanian mercenaries, originally employed by the Syrcusan tyrant Agathokles, seized the city of Messana in 289 BC. In the following period (for perhaps the first century of their occupation) they continued to use the Oscan language in inscribed documents, and a number of texts survive. They called themselves the ‘sons of Mamers’ (an Italic equivalent of Mars), and so the Mamertini, and Messana in the Roman period was sometimes called the civitas Mamertina. Oscan was an Italic language, spoken throughout much of central and southern Italy, and remained in use and visible down to the end of the Roman Republican period (first century BC), before being wholly replaced by Latin. Although other groups of Campanian mercenaries settled in Sicily in the Hellenistic period (e.g. at Entella in the fourth century BC), Messana is the only settlement in Sicily which has produced written evidence for Oscan use. All of these texts, although in the Oscan language, use the Greek alphabet: this is the practice across much of southern Italy (Lucania and Bruttium), whereas a distinctive Oscan alphabet was normally used elsewhere (including Campania). There is some linguistic evidence to suggest that the use of the Greek alphabet in Messana was particularly influenced by the surrounding Sicilian use of Greek.
               The practice of stamping tiles and bricks during production was common in antiquity, whether publicly produced (as in the case) or privately (in which case the name of the owner of the brick works is most common). Greek examples (ΤΑΥΡΟΜΕΝΙΤΑΝ (‘of the Tauromenitani’) are known, for example, from Taormina.
               </p>
         </div>
